            <p>
                <m>\text{gcd}(6,21)=3</m> and <m>3|21</m> so the congruence has solutions, and, in fact <m>3</m> incongruent solutions.  In this example, it is easy to fish for a solution: <m>x=6</m> works.
                The three solutions are then
                <md>
                    6, 6+\frac{21}{3}=13, 6+2\cdot \frac{21}{3}=20
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                The numbers are a little larger here.  The Euclidean algorthim can be used to find <m>\text{gcd}(36, 102)=6</m> and <m>6 \nmid 8</m> so there are no solutions to the congruence.
            </p>
