        <li>
            <p>
                Use the Euclidean Algorithm to find <m>\text{gcd}(140,301)=7</m>.  Since <m>7|133</m> there are solutions.  We can use the Euclidean Algorthim to find one solution.  From working the Euclidean Algorithm backwards we have 
                <md>
                    -15\cdot 140 + 7\cdot 301=7
                </md> and

                <md>
                    (-15 \cdot 19 )140+(7\cdot 19)301=133
                </md>
                and reduce modulo <m>301</m> to obtain:

                <md>
                    <mrow> 140\cdot -285 \amp \equiv 133 \pmod{301}</mrow>
                    <mrow>140 \cdot 16 \amp  \equiv 133 \pmod{301}.</mrow>
                </md>
                
                The seven incongruent solutions are:
                <md>
                    16, 16+\frac{301}{7}=59, 16+2\cdot43=102, 145, 188, 231, 274.
                </md>
                
                
                
